<em><small>1 message(s) skipped by filter settings</em></small>
<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0><tr><td>
	     <table class=mform  border=0 cellpadding=1 cellspacing=0 width=100%>
	     <form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f96661085417187>
	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=classes.html?class=8&mid=96661085417187>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=8&mid=96661085417187>RE: Group combat</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=8&mid=96661085417187#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Fri, Aug 18th 11:00 AM 2000</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=402><span id=Sage>Sage</span></a><br><b><span id=Sage>Sage</span></b><br><span id=notbold>18 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent [4.50]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>The first rule of grouping is "Know Thy Group".&nbsp;&nbsp;Druids are good in lots of areas, but there's usually a better class in any one of them.<br><br>If you're grouped with a cleric, let them buff and heal.  They have slightly better buffs than your skin line at the same levels and they don't stack.  Plus, a good cleric will often do small heals with one of their buff line rather than cast the big heal they have memed... this won't work if it won't overwrite your skin buff. Although their buff is slightly better, the ones that are similar won't overwrite each other. Depending on level, your may have the same heal spell, but you should let them heal and use your mana elsewhere (unless the mob gets on the cleric, in which case you'll probably need to heal them ;-).<br><br>With an enchanter who's doing crowd control, just DOT the mob you're concentrating on (you should be assisting the tank).  Also, enchanters and mages get better damage shields for your tanks than you have, so let them cast them.  And make sure your enchanter keeps that cool breeze blowing (clarity). ;-)<br><br>Shamen are the closest combat-spell wise to druids, and they have more buffs and debuffs.  You should coordinate attack plans with them.  Their strength buffs are better, but they don't have something like the skin line.  They get SoW before druids, but they're equivalent for the same levels.<br><br>Unless you're camping a particular spawn or have a ranger along, you're likely to be the one pulling mobs because of tracking.  Snare to pull and run back.  With red or yellow mobs, you don't want to damage the creature until he's had time to get really mad at your tank.  Especially on reds, hold off on the DOT's until your tank has taken some significant damage.  Try the flame one first to lower AC for your tank, even though it's resisted more often.  After that, do the swarm line DOT.  If the flame one was resisted, try it again after that.  You should med (and heal if no cleric is around) until the mob is in the last bubble of health, then you can DD blast if you've got enough mana.</p>&nbsp;<br> </td></td></tr>
